    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1975-09-09T08:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1975-09-09T08:30:00-05:00" n="188"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d188">
                <head>188. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d188fn1"
                        >Source: Ford Library, National Security Adviser, Memoranda of
                        Conversations, 1973–1977, Box 15. Secret; <gloss target="#t_Nodis_1"
                            >Nodis</gloss>. The meeting was held in the Oval Office.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1975-09-09T09:30:00-04:00"
                            >September 9, 1975, 9:30 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>President <persName corresp="#p_FGR_1">Ford</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>, Secretary
                        of State and Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs</item>
                    <item>Lt. General <persName corresp="#p_SB_1">Brent Scowcroft</persName>, Deputy
                        Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs</item>
                </list>
                <p>President: I would moderate your comments on Scoop. We want to beat him on
                    decontrol—that would be another kick in the teeth.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: Okay. I was thinking of
                    verging on refusal to appear, but I will just stall.</p>
                <p>President: I would. Don’t bait him. Say it is better for you to appear before the
                    full committee.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: We have a reply from the
                        Soviets.<note n="2" xml:id="d188fn2">See <ref target="#d185fn3">footnote 3,
                            Document 185</ref>.</note> Their first was belligerent. This one is more
                    plaintive.</p>
                <p>President: This is certainly more moderate.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: I think we should set a date
                    for Geneva if we can get Israel to agree. We shouldn’t put Israel under pressure
                    on Syria so soon after this. We could tell Syria the Soviets put so much
                    pressure on we agreed to Geneva.</p>
                <p>President: When would it be?</p>
                <pb facs="0781" n="750" xml:id="pg_750"/>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: The important thing is to
                    agree. Then we could slip the date until January.</p>
                <p>If Israel had sense it would agree to a significant move on the Golan. That would
                    get Syria off our back for years. They need some symbolic gesture.</p>
                <p>President: Okay.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: I didn’t know the Polish and
                    Romanian Ministers of Agriculture were coming here. <persName corresp="#p_BEL_1"
                        >Butz</persName> could have helped us there by stopping them.</p>
                <p>President: Don<note n="3" xml:id="d188fn3">Donald <persName corresp="#p_RD_2"
                            >Rumsfeld</persName>.</note> said <persName corresp="#p_BEL_1"
                        >Butz</persName> didn’t get my messages so I told him to go back to him and
                    make it clear to him. He did it.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: If we could let <persName
                        corresp="#p_BLI_1">Brezhnev</persName> go to the Politburo and say he got
                    five million more tons because of Helsinki.</p>
                <p>President: If we can get a deal on grain and freight rates, we would be in good
                    shape.</p>
                <p>[Discussion of freight rates and what we can get.]<note n="4" xml:id="d188fn4"
                        >Brackets in the original.</note>
                </p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of oil, foreign assistance to Turkey and Egypt, and
                    the U.S. defense budget.]</p>
            </div>
